-align: -2.171ex; width:32.791ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
bar {x}}=3D{\frac {w_{1}x_{1}+w_{2}x_{2}+\cdots +w_{n}x_{n}}{w_{1}+w_{2}+\c=
dots +w_{n}}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, data elements with a high weight contribute more to the weigh=
ted mean than do elements with a low weight. The weights may not be negativ=
e in order for the equation to work<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_arithmetic_mean#cite_n=
ote-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>. Some may be zero, but not all of them (since division by=
 zero is not allowed).
</p><p>The formulas are simplified when the weights are normalized such tha=
t they sum up to 1, i.e., <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-=
inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=
=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" altt=
ext=3D"{\textstyle \sum \limits _{i=3D1}^{n}{w_{i}'}=3D1}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <munderover>
