<p>Gatz et al. mention that the above formulation was published by Endlich =
et al. (1988) when treating the weighted mean as a combination of a weighte=
d total estimator divided by an estimator of the population size,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
eighted_arithmetic_mean#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> based on the formulation pu=
blished by Cochran (1977), as an approximation to the ratio mean. However, =
Endlich et al. didn't seem to publish this derivation in their paper (even =
though they mention they used it), and Cochran's book includes a slightly d=
ifferent formulation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cochran1977_2-2" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_arithmetic_mean#cite_n=
ote-Cochran1977-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D=
"Page / location: 155">:=E2=80=8A155=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Still, it's almo=
st identical to the formulations described in previous sections.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Replication-based_estimator=
s">Replication-based estimators</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
